Cabot Microelectronics Dominated CMP Slurry Revenues In 2016 While Versum Materials Slid - Cabot Microelectronics Corporation (NASDAQ:CCMP) | Seeking AlphaSign in / Join NowGO»Cabot Microelectronics Dominated CMP Slurry Revenues In 2016 While Versum Materials SlidMar.20.17 | About: Cabot Microelectronics (CCMP) Robert Castellano Chipmakers, solar, macro, research analystThe Information NetworkSummaryCabot Microelectronics led the semiconductor CMP slurry business with a market share more than twice that of its closest competitor in 2016.Versum Materials slid from second place to third as it lost share to Japanese suppliers Hitachi Chemical, Fujimi and FijiFilm.Cabot Microelectronics and Versum Materials lost market share to Asian slurry suppliers in 2016. Chemical Mechanical Planarization (NYSE:CMP) is a process used in semiconductor manufacturing whereby the surface of the wafer is leveled and smoothed using abrasive slurries. The process is used following every deposition-etch step and is critical to precise lithography patterning. One of the growth drivers for CMP slurry is 3D NAND and 3D FinFET devices. I noted in a January 26, 2017 Seeking Alpha article entitled "Applied Materials: 42% Exposure To EUV Lithography Will Stunt Long-Term Growth" that: "Current DUV immersion is viable for processing devices with 30nm features. Below that, engineers employ multiple patterning steps as a way of extending the DUV lithography tool. These multiple processing steps are deposition-etch intensively, utilizing equipment from Applied Materials (NASDAQ:AMAT) and Lam Research (NASDAQ:LRCX) (and others). In other words, semiconductor manufacturers are utilizing multiple patterning processes, requiring extensive use of deposition and etch equipment, to avoid purchasing the extremely expensive EUV lithography equipment." So until EUV becomes production worthy over the next couple of years when the 7nm node is reached, CMP will benefit from the extension of immersion DUV using multiple patterning. EUV will only be utilized in the foreseeable future by Intel (NASDAQ:INTC), TSMC and Samsung Electronics (OTC:SSNLF). Unfortunately Cabot Microelectronics (NASDAQ:CCMP) has a 30% exposure to EUV because TSMC and Samsung each accounted for approximately 15% of revenue in 2016. But again, the impact of EUV on CCMP is long term. According to our report entitled "CMP Technology: Competition, Products, Markets," Cabot Microelectronics maintained its dominance in the CMP slurry business, although market share dropped one point. The company is facing competition from Korean CMP slurry companies KC Tech, Soulbrain, and Cheil for its position at Samsung Electronics. According to the report, Versum Materials (NYSE:VSM) dropped from second to third place in the CMP market as the company was replaced at the number two position by Hitachi Chemical. Versum lost more than one point in share not only to Hitachi Chemical, but to other Japanese suppliers Fujimi and FijiFilm. VSM's exposure to EUV is even worse. In fiscal 2016, Intel, Samsung, and TSMC accounted for 47% of sales. These are company-wide sales, not just CMP slurry, as the company does not transparently provide these type of data. Versum officially spun off from Air Products (NYSE:APD) on October 1, 2016, and then began operations as an independent, public company. Prior to the spin off, the company operated as DA Nanomaterials, which had been a joint venture between APD and DuPont (NYSE:DD) until APD purchased DD's 50% share in 2012. I discussed the spin off in a December 1, 2015 Seeking Alpha article entitled "Air Products - The More Things Change The More They Remain The Same." Dow Chemical (NYSE:DOW) maintained sixth place behind the above mentioned companies. Investor takeaway CCMP is one of the original suppliers of CMP slurry, having spun off of Cabot Corp (NYSE:CBT) in 2000. It has an established customer base and counts TSMC and Samsung Electronics among its largest customers. It lost market share in the past in the copper slurry business but continues to be strong in Tungsten and Dielectric slurries. The company continues to grow organically and through acquisitions, particularly in the CMP pad business. VSM is strong in Copper slurries and is focusing on enhancing its shallow trench isolation (NYSE:STI) slurry product, but the STI slurry sector is dominated by Hitachi Chemical and other companies such as Ferro Corp. (NYSE:FOE) are also working on improving their STI product. VSM has a strong customer base in Asia, but competition from Japanese and Korean slurry suppliers is eroding market share. 

Disclosure: I/we have no positions in any stocks mentioned, and no plans to initiate any positions within the next 72 hours. 
I wrote this article myself, and it expresses my own opinions. I am not receiving compensation for it (other than from Seeking Alpha). I have no business relationship with any company whose stock is mentioned in this article.
Editor's Note: This article discusses one or more securities that do not trade on a major U.S. exchange. Please be aware of the risks associated with these stocks.About this article:ExpandAuthor payment: $35 + $0.01/page view. Authors of PRO articles receive a minimum guaranteed payment of $150-500.Tagged: Investing Ideas, Quick Picks & Lists, Technology, Semiconductor - Integrated CircuitsWant to share your opinion on this article? Add a comment.Disagree with this article? Submit your own.To report a factual error in this article, click hereFollow Robert Castellano and get email alerts









