                Cabot Corporation            








News about Cabot Corporation, including commentary and archival articles published in The New York Times.                    











Latest Articles






DealBook

                    Cabot to Buy Norit for $1.1 Billion                
The Boston-based chemicals company agreed to buy Norit, a Dutch manufacturer of activated carbon that is used in chemical reactions, for $1.1 billion.










COMPANY NEWS

                    CABOT TO SELL STAKE IN MICROELECTRONICS UNIT                
The Cabot Corporation said yesterday that it would spin off its remaining 80.5 percent stake in the Cabot Microelectronics Corporation, a producer of chemicals used in making computer chips, three months after it first sold shares to the public. The shares of Cabot Microelectronics, which is based in Aurora, Ill., rose 37.5 cents, to $48, more than double the price of $20 at which they were first sold to the public on April 4, and the total shares are worth more than $1 billion. The Cabot Corporation, a Boston-based maker of chemicals used in tires, polishes and oil-drilling fluids, said the spinoff would be distributed as a dividend to Cabot Microelectronics shareholders. The parent company's stock rose $1.8125 a share, to $33.50.










COMPANY NEWS

                    CABOT IS SELLING GAS UNIT TO TRACTEBEL FOR $680 MILLION                
The Cabot Corporation agreed yesterday to sell its Cabot LNG unit to Tractebel Inc. for $680 million. Tractebel is a unit of the Tractebel Group, an energy and services company. It handles energy activities for the French conglomerate Suez Lyonnaise des Eaux. Cabot LNG imports and distributes liquefied natural gas to utilities and industrial companies in the Northeastern United States. It has annual sales of $425 million. The Cabot Corporation, based in Boston, is a specialty chemical, materials and energy company. It had 1999 sales of $1.7 billion. Its shares rose $1.625 yesterday, to $31.75.










COMPANY NEWS

                    CABOT TO TAKE A $54 MILLION EARNINGS CHARGE                
The Cabot Corporation, the largest provider of carbon black, which is used to reinforce rubber products, said yesterday that it would take a charge of about $54 million in its third quarter to reduce the value of an Indonesian plant and to reflect disappointing yields from a Pennsylvania ore recovery project. Cabot said about $38 million, or 51 cents a diluted share, of the charge was to write down the value of one of its carbon black plants in West Java, Indonesia. The Boston-based Cabot also said $16 million, or 21 cents, of the charge stemmed from a ''very disappointing'' yield at the tantalum ore project. Tantalum is used to make electronic capacitors and nuclear reactor parts.










COMPANY NEWS

                    CABOT SELLS COAL UNIT TO NEXGEN RESOURCES                
The Cabot Corporation sold its Tuco Inc. coal inventory and contract business to the closely held Nexgen Resources Corporation and the Republic Financial Corporation for $77 million. The purchase price is subject to adjustments, the companies said. Tuco owns the coal inventory at two coal-fueled power plants owned by the Southwestern Public Service Company of Amarillo, Tex. It also manages all aspects of acquiring, delivering and handling coal for Southwestern Public Service. Cabot, based in Boston, makes specialty chemicals, including carbon black used in tires and rubber products.










COMPANY NEWS

                    CABOT TO SELL STAKE IN SAFETY EQUIPMENT DIVISION                
The Cabot Corporation said yesterday that it had agreed to sell a stake in its safety equipment unit to the management of the division and to Vestar Equity Partners L.P. for $205 million. Cabot expects a gain of about $125 million when the sale of the Cabot Safety Corporation is completed in July. Cabot and Vestar will own equal amounts of Cabot Safety's common and preferred stock, and Cabot Safety's management will own about 15 percent of the common stock. Cabot Safety, based in Boston, makes hearing and face protection equipment, prescription safety eyewear and respiratory products. Shares of Cabot rose 75 cents, to $42.75, on the New York Stock Exchange.










COMPANY NEWS

                    SOUTHWESTERN PUBLIC TO GET TUCO BACK FROM CABOT                
The Cabot Corporation said yesterday that it had agreed to sell Tuco Inc., its coal-handling subsidiary, back to the Southwestern Public Service Company for $75 million. The sale would include all of the coal inventory and coal contract operations managed by Tuco. Cabot, based in Boston, acquired Tuco for $33.8 million in 1979 from Southwestern Public Service, of Amarillo, Tex. Cabot said it expected most of the proceeds from the sale to be reinvested in Cabot's core specialty chemicals business.











                    Cabot Offers 2 Issues of Notes                
LEAD: The Cabot Corporation is offering two note issues totaling $250 million through underwriters led by Merrill Lynch Capital Markets.










BUSINESS PEOPLE

                    President of Cabot Chosen to Be Chief                
LEAD: Samuel W. Bodman, president and chief operating officer of the Cabot Corporation, an old-line chemical, energy and materials company based in Boston, will assume the additional post of chief executive in February, the company said yesterday.










AROUND THE WORLD

                    Meeting Seeks to End Fighting in Sri Lanka                
A seven-nation meeting of South Asian national leaders opened today with intense efforts by India and Sri Lanka to resolve the protracted ethnic strife in Sri Lanka.














BUSINESS PEOPLE

                    Fidelity's President Taking Cabot Post                
Samuel W. Bodman is leaving the presidency of the FMR Corporation, a financial services holding company that includes the big Fidelity group of mutual funds, to be president and chief operating officer of the Cabot Corporation. Cabot is an energy and specialty chemicals company based in Boston, also the home of FMR, which is commonly called Fidelity Investments. Mr. Bodman, who was traveling and not available for an interview, will succeed Robert A. Charpie, 61 years old, as president, and Mr. Charpie will continue as chairman and chief executive. The changes are effective Jan. 1.











                    Cabot Earnings Jump                
The Cabot Corporation, a Bostonbased producer of metal alloys and chemicals and operator in the energy field, reported that it had sharply increased net income for the quarter ending Sept. 30, which is also the end of its fiscal year.











                    COMPANY NEWS; Korvettes to Miss A Debt Repayment Mitel Tender Offer Countered by NCR Synfuel Energy Files For U.S. Financing E.P.A. Approves Cyanamid Product Diamond Shamrock Faces Tesoro Suit Celanese Purchasing Chemicals Concern Columbia Gas Unit In Pipeline Venture Triton Oil Wins French Drilling Pact Western Union Service Curtailed Ingersoll-Rand Buys Oil Equipment Unit Savin Reduces Copier Prices                












                    EXECUTIVE CHANGES                












                    OCCIDENTAL OIL TURNS A PROFIT; But Third-Quarter Earnings Fail to Meet Requirement on Preferred Dividend Occidental Petroleum Reports a Profit                
The Occidental Petroleum Corporation had a profit of $269,000 in the third quarter of this year, which was insufficient to cover preferred-dividend requirements of $4.8-million, the company reported late yesterday.











                    Zapata to Exchange Southdown Stock; Companies Announce Merger Actions                
Directors of Zapata Norness, Inc., and Southdown, Inc., approved yesterday an agreement in principle providing for the exchange by Southdown of certain of its real estate interests for all of the shares of common and preferred stock of Southdown presently owned by Zapata.











                    Executive Changes                












                    EXECUTIVE CHANGES                












                    Executive Post Filled By Cabot Corporation                



























